<br>
Vi pretty much said, &quot;bah you want focus items? HERE HAVE FOCUS ITEMS! and made them summonable to the point where they're pretty much just an innate ability. They might as well just have MADE it an innate ability. High level players are removing their ntov/high end loots to use these items now (thx 8,5 sec CH, etc), talk about @#%$ up risk vs. reward.<br>
<br>
In fact, with a 15% decrease of casting cost, casting time, agro, +15% to damage, all which is summoned equipment, you may as well give Magicians Summon Primal weapon.<br>
<br>
Compare a L60 warrior who is in a small guild, or has few friends and just sits around Sebelis all day, acquiring experience and selling fungi tunics, with a main tank from a large guild. Compare the dps/effectiveness in tanking of the two warriors--there's gonna be a HUGE difference.<br>
<br>
Then look at a L60 wizard who bought the account naked off Ebay to port themselves around to a L60 wizard in a high end guild in your &quot;Team 0wnz0r ks style&quot; or whatever. Well the latter one has focus items!---Oh @#%$, thats right, so does that completely naked wizard, after talking to random_LFG_mage01 and offering him a translocate to next_dungeon02 to find a group. The difference comes down to a larger mana pool, few more hp, and nice resists, but both wizards can burn down and ks a mob, translocate, and all.<br>
<br>
Ancient spells are supposed to help show the difference between the last wizard example (except for all caster classes), but giving magicians give or six free summonable focus items which *everyone* can use is a step in the wrong direction, and tries to generalize caster classes even more.<br>
<br>
another example, of why the risk vs reward is @#%$ up:<br>
<br>
